   <text>
      <body>
         <div type="essay">
            <head>
               <bibl>
                  <author type="writer">
                     <name>
                        <ref target="people.html#InchbaldMrs">Elizabeth Inchbald</ref>
                     </name>
                  </author>
                  <title type="main" level="a">REMARKS [on <hi rendition="#italics"><title><ref
                              target="people.html#Macbeth">Macbeth</ref></title></hi>].
                        <note>"Remarks." <hi rendition="#italics"><title><title><ref
                                    target="people.html#Macbeth">Macbeth</ref></title>; A Tragedy,
                              In Five Acts; By <ref target="people.html#ShakespeareWilliam">William
                                 Shakspeare</ref>. As Performed at the Theatres Royal, <ref
                                 target="people.html#CoventGarden">Covent Garden</ref> and <ref
                                 target="people.html#DruryLane">Drury Lane</ref>. Printed Under the
                              Authority of the Managers From the Prompt Book. With Remarks by <ref
                                 target="people.html#InchbaldMrs">Mrs. Inchbald</ref></title></hi>,
                        London: Printed for Longman, Hurst, Rees, and Orme, Paternoster Row, pp.
                        3-5. <hi rendition="#italics"><title level="m">The British Theatre; or, A
                              Collection of Plays, Which Are Acted At the Theatres Royal, <ref
                                 target="people.html#DruryLane">Drury Lane</ref>, <ref
                                 target="people.html#CoventGarden">Covent Garden</ref>, and <ref
                                 target="people.html#Haymarket">Haymarket</ref>. Printed Under the
                              Authority of the Managers from the Prompt Books. With Biographical and
                              Critical Remarks, by <ref target="people.html#InchbaldMrs">Mrs.
                                 Inchbald.</ref></title></hi> In Twenty-Five Volumes. Vol. IV. <hi
                           rendition="#italics"><title><ref target="people.html#LearKingofBritain"
                                 >King Lear</ref></title></hi>. <hi rendition="#italics"><title><ref
                                 target="people.html#Cunobelinus">Cymbeline</ref></title></hi>. <hi
                           rendition="#italics"><title><ref target="people.html#Macbeth"
                                 >Macbeth</ref></title></hi>. <hi rendition="#italics"><title><ref
                                 target="people.html#CaesarJulius">Julius Cæsar</ref></title></hi>.
                           <hi rendition="#italics"><title><ref target="people.html#AntoniusMarcus"
                                 >Antony</ref> and <ref
                                 target="people.html#CleopatraVIIQueenofEgypt"
                              >Cleopatra</ref></title></hi>. London: Printed for Longman, Hurst,
                        Rees, and Orme, Paternoster Row. 1808. The first performance of this play
                        was staged at the Globe Theatre in 1606. Laura DeWitt and Mary A. Waters
                        edited this essay for <hi rendition="#italics">The Criticism Archive</hi>. </note>
                     <lb rendition="#center"/>______ </title>
               </bibl>
            </head>
            <p>In this grand tragic opera is combined that which is terrific, sublime, infernal.
               Spirits are called from the bottomless pit, to give additional horror to the crimes
               which are here perpetrated. Yet supernatural agency is produced and conducted by such
               natural means, that spectators return again to their childish credulity, and tremble,
               as in the nursery, at a witch and a goblin. </p>

            <p>It is impossible to contemplate the consistent disposition of able actors, of
               appropriate habiliments, and of picturesque scenery, with which this tragedy is now
               embellished, at the London theatres, and not boldly demand&#8212;where was <ref
                  target="people.html#GarrickDavid">Garrick</ref>'s taste, his innovating judgment,
               his common sense, and common feelings, as a connoisseur in his art, that he could
               perform this historical tragedy<note>In 1744, <ref target="people.html#GarrickDavid"
                     >David Garrick</ref> assumed the role of <ref target="people.html#Macbeth"
                     >Macbeth</ref>, advertising his performance to be "as <ref
                     target="people.html#ShakespeareWilliam">Shakespeare</ref> wrote it," rather
                  than the then-standard version adapted by <ref
                     target="people.html#DavenantWilliam">Sir William Davenant</ref>. However, <ref
                     target="people.html#GarrickDavid">Garrick</ref>'s claim was misleading, as he
                  retained many of <ref target="people.html#DavenantWilliam">Davenant</ref>'s
                  popular changes and added a lengthy monologue for <ref
                     target="people.html#Macbeth">Macbeth</ref> which he himself
                  wrote.</note>&#8212;<ref target="people.html#Macbeth">Macbeth</ref>, of ancient
               Scotland&#8212;with the characters dressed in coats, waistcoats, and hats, so as to
               place the scene in modern times, or every scene in England.</p>

            <p><ref target="people.html#GarrickDavid">Garrick</ref> had taste, it is said; and so,
               they say, had his admirers: yet, taste like this, would be now exploded.&#8212;So, it
               might be insinuated, perhaps, would be the acting of those days, could it have been
                  pre-<fw type="sig"><hi rendition="#smcaps">b 2</hi></fw><pb n="4"/>served, along
               with the old attire, for the inspection of critics of the present era.</p>

            <p>On this impossibility the actor's art triumphs over, yet sinks beneath, every other.
               He has no rivals to vanquish, but cotemporaries. He has no former artists to excel,
               but such as cannot come forth to claim the preference, or to crouch to superior
               skill.</p>

            <p>The story of <ref target="people.html#Macbeth">Macbeth</ref> is founded on Scottish
               history, and may be traced in the works of many writers. But, in a production called
                     "<title><ref target="people.html#ShakespeareWilliam">Shakspeare</ref>
                  Illustrated</title>,"<note><hi rendition="#italics"><title>The Whole Historical
                        Dramas of <ref target="people.html#ShakespeareWilliam">William
                           Shakspeare</ref> Illustrated, by an Assemblage of Portraits of the Royal,
                        Noble, and Other Persons Mentioned, Together with Those of Commentators,
                        Actors, and Views of Castles, Towns, &amp;c., (Engraved by Harding) with
                        Short Biographical and Topographical Accounts</title></hi> (1793).</note>
               every event of that usurper's life is collected from different histories, and given
               at large.</p>

            <p>So conspicuous are the various excellencies contained in this tragedy, there is no
               cause whatever to point them out to the reader; for, if he cannot see them at once,
               it is vain to direct his sight.</p>

            <p>But to those, who are unacquainted with the effect wrought by theatrical action and
               decoration, it may not be superfluous to say&#8212;The huge rocks, the enormous
               caverns, and blasted heaths of Scotland, in the scenery;&#8212;the highland warrior's
               dress, of centuries past, worn by the soldiers and their generals;&#8212;the splendid
               robes and banquet at the royal court held at Fores;<note>Castle Forres is the home of
                  Duncan, King of Scotland prior to his murder by Macbeth.</note>&#8212;the awful,
               yet inspiring music, which accompanies words assimilated to each sound;&#8212;and,
               above all&#8212;the fear, the terror, the remorse;&#8212;the agonizing throbs and
               throes, which speak in looks, whispers, sudden starts, and writhings, by <ref
                  target="people.html#KembleJohn">Kemble</ref> and <ref
                  target="people.html#SiddonsSarah">Mrs. Siddons</ref>, all tending to one great
                  precept&#8212;<hi rendition="#italics">Thou shalt not murder</hi>,&#8212;render
               this play one of the most impressive moral lessons which the stage exhibits.</p>
            <pb n="5"/>

            <p>It was the tragedy of <title><ref target="people.html#Macbeth">Macbeth</ref></title>,
               which conferred upon <ref target="people.html#ShakespeareWilliam">Shakspeare</ref>
               the distinguished honour of receiving a letter, written with his sovereign's own
               hand, <ref target="people.html#JamesIKingofEngland">James the First</ref>, in
               testimony of his high admiration of the work!<note>It is believed that <hi
                     rendition="#italics"><title><ref target="people.html#Macbeth"
                        >Macbeth</ref></title></hi> was written, in part, as a form of flattery to
                     <ref target="people.html#JamesIKingofEngland">King James I</ref>, who was a
                  patron of <ref target="people.html#ShakespeareWilliam">Shakespeare</ref>'s acting
                  company. <hi rendition="#italics"><title><ref target="people.html#Macbeth"
                           >Macbeth</ref></title></hi> played to <ref
                     target="people.html#JamesIKingofEngland">James</ref>' Scottish heritage,
                  support of witch trials, and particular detestation for regicide following the
                  Gunpowder Plot of 1605 (an unsuccessful attempt on <ref
                     target="people.html#JamesIKingofEngland">James</ref>' life). <ref
                     target="people.html#JamesIKingofEngland">James</ref> also believed himself to
                  be a descendent of Banquo, a Scottish general in the army of Duncan, King of
                  Scotland.</note></p>

            <p><ref target="people.html#SteevensGeorge">Steevens</ref> calls this play, "The first
               of all dramatic enjoyments."<note>From <hi rendition="#italics"><title>The Plays of
                           <ref target="people.html#ShakespeareWilliam">William Shakspeare</ref>,
                        With the Corrections and Illustrations of Various Commentators</title></hi>
                  (1793), vol. 7, p. 322.</note></p>

            <p><ref target="people.html#JohnsonSamuel">Johnson</ref> says, in apology for some
               occurrences contained in it, "I know not whether it may not be said, in defence of
               some parts which now seem improbable, that, in <ref
                  target="people.html#ShakespeareWilliam">Shakspeare</ref>'s time, it was necessary
               to warn credulity against vain and delusive predictions."<note>From <hi
                     rendition="#italics"><title>The Plays of <ref
                           target="people.html#ShakespeareWilliam">William Shakespeare</ref>, With
                        the Corrections and Illustrations of Various Commentators</title></hi>
                  (1765), vol. 6, p. 484.</note></p>
            <fw type="sig">
               <hi rendition="#smcaps">b 3</hi>
            </fw>
         </div>
      </body>
